{
  "text": "Due to their importance, not only to genetics, but also to other areas of knowledge, several statistical methods of (co)variance estimates have been proposed throughout the years. More recently, the introduction of computer intensive statistical methods and the increasing adoption of Bayesian approaches and techniques, generally referred to as Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, has been favored. In this respect, Gibbs sampling (GS) is a Monte Carlo numerical integration method that allows inferences to be made about joint or marginal distributions, even if appropriate densities cannot be explicitly formed [CITATION_1] . The use of GS allows analysis of Bayesian posterior distributions that had been computationally intractable due to the numerical integration required to obtain those distributions. The method presents properties of interest for animal improvement and extensive statistical resources capable of supplying more and more accurate estimates.",
